  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Should I use two single pages, or both sides of a single piece of paper for a two-page resume?",
  "response": "When deciding whether to use two single pages or both sides of a single piece of paper for a two-page resume, consider the following factors:\n\n1. **Professionalism and Aesthetics**: Using both sides of a single piece of high-quality paper can present a more cohesive and professional appearance. It also reduces the risk of one page getting misplaced. Ensure that the printer or copier you use can print clearly on both sides without any bleed-through.\n\n2. **Applicability to the Industry**: Certain industries may have preferences or norms. For instance, creative fields might appreciate a more visually appealing format, while traditional corporate settings might favor simplicity and readability. Research the norms in your target industry.\n\n3. **ATS (Applicant Tracking Systems)**: If you\u2019re applying through an online system, be aware that some Applicant Tracking Systems may have issues reading double-sided documents. In such cases, using two separate pages might be safer.\n\n4. **Printing and Distribution**: If you plan to mail your resume or hand it out at job fairs, consider the ease of handling. Two separate pages might be easier for someone to read quickly, but they also run a higher risk of getting separated.\n\n5. **Content Layout**: Ensure that the transition from one page to the next is smooth and logical. If using a double-sided format, make sure the content flows well from the end of the first page to the beginning of the second. If using two separate pages, headers and footers should clearly indicate the page number and your name.\n\n**Recommendation**: If you are submitting your resume digitally, using a single document (whether it's double-sided when printed or not) is generally preferable. This format is easier for electronic systems to handle and ensures that your document remains intact.\n\nIf you are submitting a hard copy and confident in the quality of the printing, using both sides of a single sheet can look polished and professional. However, if there's any doubt about the print quality or if you're distributing your resume in settings where it might be easier to handle two separate pages, then using two single pages is a safe choice.\n\nUltimately, ensure that your resume is easy to read, well-formatted, and professionally presented, regardless of the format you choose.",
